  "method": "We propose Robust-Without-Target (RWT), a two-stage recipe that combines training-time shift-agnostic regularization with a test-time adapter and safety wrapper. At training, we (a) replace deterministic data dropout/reweighting with a probabilistic, influence-bounded sampler that caps the gradient of per-example sampling probabilities; and (b) add a multiresolution auxiliary head to regularize features across granularities. Concretely, we compute per-example influence signals on a held-out split and sample with a linear/sigmoid function whose slope σ bounds sensitivity; this mimics distributionally robust training within a χ²-ball around the empirical distribution while avoiding overconfidence on the validation mix. In parallel, we train a light auxiliary prediction head at a coarser or alternative resolution (e.g., class clusters, attribute tags, or subword/character analogs), applying a weighted multi-task loss to stabilize semantics across unseen axes.\n\nNext, we meta-learn a test-time adaptation operator across synthetic shifts, without access to the true target distribution. We define a set of plausible shift generators (e.g., style/texture perturbations, resolution changes, occlusion/masking, label-imbalance resampling) and construct inner–outer loops: an inner loop performs a few test-time steps using unsupervised/self-supervised objectives (entropy minimization, consistency across augmentations, and agreement between main and auxiliary heads); the outer loop optimizes the base model so that post-adaptation performance on held-out views improves. This yields a MAML-like adapter that can quickly specialize to novel conditions using only the incoming test stream.\n\nAt inference, we attach a training-free, non-parametric error-compensation memory. The system stores a rolling buffer of recent test representations, base predictions, and any available outcomes; when labels are unavailable or delayed, it stores proxy nonconformity scores (e.g., softmax margin, disagreement across augmentations/heads). For each new input, we retrieve similar states by attention over the buffer and estimate a residual bias to add to the base prediction, with a temperature and clamp to keep corrections bounded. The buffer is refreshed online, enabling self-correction even under rapid drift.\n\nFinally, we wrap predictions with an online-calibrated conformal safety layer. We score each output with a monotone, model-derived nonconformity (e.g., 1 − max softmax or margin) and maintain a threshold κ updated with a decaying-step-size rule to target 1−α coverage. Below κ we return a point prediction; above κ we either return a small set (top-k covering set) or abstain, depending on the application. This provides coverage guarantees and graceful degradation under unforeseen shifts. The full system requires no target-domain samples at training: robustness comes from influence-bounded sampling and multiresolution regularization, quick specialization is delivered by the meta-learned adapter, rapid local bias correction comes from the error memory, and reliability is enforced by online conformal calibration.",
  "rationale": "Unknown, out-of-support shifts can break models along axes unseen in training. RWT addresses this in layered fashion: (1) bounded-gradient probabilistic sampling reduces the model’s sensitivity to any one training mix and improves worst-case risk within a principled uncertainty set, while multiresolution multitask losses pull features toward semantics that persist across scales, reducing overfit to spurious axes; (2) a meta-learned adapter trains the model to improve after a small, unsupervised adaptation step on synthetic, diverse perturbations, enabling quick specialization at deployment without target-domain pre-exposure; (3) a non-parametric error memory adds fast, training-free local corrections that follow the current stream, even with weak or delayed supervision; and (4) conformal calibration converts raw scores into coverage-controlled decisions, ensuring reliability despite residual mismatch.\n\nBecause no single mechanism fully protects against unseen axes, the combination is key: influence-bounded training and multiresolution regularization make the base model broadly stable; the adapter and memory handle rapid or structural drifts at test time; and conformal thresholds bound risk when uncertainty spikes. Crucially, none of these components require observing the true target distribution during training.",
