  "method": "We propose Disentangle–Separate–Adapt (DiSeA), a training and deployment recipe that forces the model to rely on label-causal features and equips it with a lightweight, unsupervised adapter for on-the-fly robustness. During supervised training on the source data, we expose the backbone to a bank of synthetic interventions that target plausible nuisance axes (e.g., style, background, color, compression, mild geometric or temporal perturbations). We train with a factorized representation z = [z_shared, z_nuis] where the predictor consumes only z_shared. A domain-adversarial head and information bottleneck discourage nuisance information in z_shared, while separate, augmentation-dependent priors over z_nuis capture systematic variation induced by each synthetic domain.\n\nTo stabilize reliance on z_shared and quantify uncertainty, we insert a prototype-based discriminative layer before the classifier. This layer learns a bank of prototypes and encourages sharp, well-separated clusters for class-relevant structure; a small auxiliary head maps the prototype activations to a calibrated confidence. We add a cross-augmentation consistency loss on predictions from different synthetic views of the same example, and a regularizer that minimizes the mutual information between z_shared and augmentation identity while maximizing it for z_nuis, aligning with the factorized design.\n\nTo better decouple content from nuisance without target data, we add a mix-and-separate auxiliary task: we create pseudo-composites by combining the content of one sample with the nuisance attributes of another (e.g., background/style swaps for images, timbre/reverb swaps for audio, style/paraphrase swaps for text) and train a small separation branch that, given the composite, predicts content and nuisance embeddings consistent with those of the original sources. This forces the shared path to carry label-relevant signal that remains stable under recombination, improving invariance to novel, unseen axes at test time.\n\nAt deployment, we keep the backbone frozen and attach a tiny input- or feature-space adapter (prompt/tuner) that updates online without labels. We perform entropy-minimization and consistency updates only on samples flagged as uncertain by the prototype confidence, using a momentum EMA with uncertainty-weighted step sizes to avoid drift. A safety gate reuses the uncertainty to control adaptation rate, snapshot and rollback the adapter when confidence drops, and abstain or escalate for extreme out-of-support inputs. Because the adapter is small and the update is unsupervised, the system can react to novel shifts it never saw during training while preserving the invariant backbone.",
  "rationale": "Generalization to axes never seen at training fails when predictors unintentionally bind to nuisance features. DiSeA tackles this by (i) explicitly factorizing representations into shared and nuisance channels with augmentation-dependent priors and adversarial decoupling, pushing the classifier to depend only on label-causal structure; (ii) enforcing prediction consistency across synthetic interventions while encouraging z_nuis to carry augmentation identity, which makes z_shared maximally invariant; and (iii) using a mix-and-separate auxiliary task to practice counterfactual recomposition, strengthening the model’s ability to ignore nuisance even for combinations absent from the source.\n\nBecause the target distribution is unavailable during training, we rely solely on synthetic interventions derived from the source and on-the-fly, label-free adaptation at test time. The uncertainty-aware prompt/adapter provides a low-risk mechanism to make small, reversible adjustments in response to real shifts, with confidence gating to prevent catastrophic drift. Together, these components yield robustness to previously unseen shift axes without needing target samples during training.",
